ic","justification":"LLM-DEP: identifying “too formal for casual tier” is model judgment quality; mocks can force flags and miss real misclassification. MULTI-STEP: regeneration is downstream orchestration, but the key failure boundary is one model decision governing handoff, so Agentic over Workflow. REJECTION-GATE: Workflow disqualified because behavior does not require validating quality across multiple model decisions, only correct flagging plus trigger.","test_description":"Use real model outputs for casual-tier scenarios and verify the tone-check step flags overly formal responses at acceptable precision/recall, then assert regeneration path is invoked when flagged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.15}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchange (user message, generated response, any regenerations) is persisted to the database with correct timestamps.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: failure is in module handoff (chat pipeline -> persistence schema/transaction). REAL-INFRA: local DB integration is sufficient; no real external network/OS primitive required. LLM-DEP: assertions are about stored records/timestamps, not model quality. REJECTION-GATE: System disqualified because behavior text only requires DB persistence correctness, reproducible with in-process/local test DB.","test_description":"Execute chat flow against a real local test database (same ORM/repository path), including a regeneration case; assert all expected records are stored with correct linkage/order and timestamp fields populated correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the tone check triggers regeneration, the second response replaces the first — the customer never sees the rejected draft.","